# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deterministic-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] DetNet operates at the IP Layer 3 routed segments using a software-defined networking layer to provide IntServ and DiffServ integration, and delivers service over lower Layer 2 bridged segments using technologies such as MPLS and IEEE 802.1 Time-Sensitive Networking.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Deterministic Networking aims to migrate time-critical, high-reliability industrial control and audio-video applications from special-purpose Fieldbus networks (HDMI, CAN bus, PROFIBUS, RS-485, RS-422/RS-232, and I²C) to packet networks and IP in particular.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] DetNet will support both the new applications and existing IT applications on the same physical network.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Standard IT infrastructure cannot efficiently handle latency-sensitive data.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Switches and routers use fundamentally uncertain algorithms for processing packet/frames, which may result in sporadic data flow.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] A common solution for smoothing out these flows is to increase buffer sizes, but this has a negative effect on delivery latency because data has to fill the buffers before transmission to the next switch or router can start.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] IEEE Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN) task group has defined deterministic algorithms for queuing, shaping and scheduling which allow each node to allocate bandwidth and latency according to requirements of each data flow, by computing the buffer size at the network switch.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] The same algorithms can be employed at higher network layers to improve delivery of IP packets and provide interoperability with TSN hardware when available.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Scheduling, shaping, limiting, and controlling transmission at each node.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Protection against misbehaving nodes (in both the data and the control planes): a flow cannot affect other flows even under high load.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Reserving resources in nodes that carry the flow.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] To reduce contention related packet loss, resources such as buffer space or link bandwidth can be assigned to the flow along the path from source to destination.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Maintaining adequate buffer storage at each node also limits maximum end-to-end latency.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] The maximum transmission rate and maximum packet size have to be explicitly defined for each flow.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Each network node along the path shall not exceed these data rates, as any packet sent out of scheduled time requires additional buffering on the next node, which may exceed its allocated resources.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] To limit data rates, traffic policing and shaping functions are applied at the ingress ports.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] This also protects regular IT traffic from misbehaving DetNet sources.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Time-of-execution fields in the packets and sub-microsecond time synchronization across all nodes are used to ensure minimum end-to-end latency and eliminate irregular delivery (jitter).
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Jitter reduces the perceived quality of audiovisual applications, and control network applications built around serial communication protocols cannot handle jitter at all.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Packet loss can also result from media errors and equipment failures.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Packet replication and elimination and packet encoding provide service protection from these failures.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Replication and elimination works by spreading the data across several explicit paths and reassembling them in-order near the destination.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Different path lengths also require additional buffering to equalize the delays and ensure bandwidth constraints after failure recovery.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Replication and elimination may be used by multiple DetNet nodes to improve protection against multiple failures.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Packet encoding uses multiple transmission units for each packet, adding redundancy and error correction information from multiple packets to each transmission unit.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] In mesh networks, topology events such as failure or recovery can impact data flow even in remote network segments.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] A side effect of route changes is out-of-order packet delivery.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Real-time networks are often based on physical rings with a simple control protocol and two ports per device for redundant paths, though at a cost of increased hop count and latency.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] DetNet routes are typically explicitly defined and do not change (at least immediately) in response to network topology events, so there are no interruptions from routing or bridging protocol negotiations.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Explicit routes can be established with RSVP-TE, Segment Routing, IS-IS, MPLS-TE label-switched path (LSP), or a software-defined networking layer.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] IETF Traffic Engineering Architecture and Signaling (TEAS) work group maintains MPLS-TE LSP and RSVP-TE protocols.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] Protocol interworking defined by IEEE 802.1CB is used to advertise TSN sub-network capabilities to DetNet flows via the Active Destination MAC and VLAN Stream identification functions.
[src:deterministic-networking/deterministic-networking] DetNet flows are matched by destination MAC address, VLAN ID and priority parameters to Stream ID and QoS requirements for talkers and listeners in the AVB/TSN sub-network.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In electronics and telecommunications, **jitter** is the deviation from true periodicity of a presumably periodic signal, often in relation to a reference clock signal.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In clock recovery applications it is called **timing jitter**.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter is a significant, and usually undesired, factor in the design of almost all communications links.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter can be quantified in the same terms as all time-varying signals, e.g., root mean square (RMS), or peak-to-peak displacement.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Also, like other time-varying signals, jitter can be expressed in terms of spectral density.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter may be caused by electromagnetic interference and crosstalk with carriers of other signals.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter can cause a display monitor to flicker, affect the performance of processors in personal computers, introduce clicks or other undesired effects in audio signals, and cause loss of transmitted data between network devices.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The amount of tolerable jitter depends on the affected application.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] in the position of a clock's edge from where it would ideally be.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Maximum error committed by a clock under test in measuring a time interval for a given period of time.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The difference between any one clock period and the ideal or average clock period.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Hence, synchronous circuitry benefits from minimizing period jitter, so that the shortest clock period approaches the average clock period.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The difference in duration of any two adjacent clock periods.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In telecommunications, the unit used for the above types of jitter is usually the unit interval (UI) which quantifies the jitter in terms of a fraction of the transmission unit period.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] This unit is useful because it scales with clock frequency and thus allows relatively slow interconnects such as T1 to be compared to higher-speed internet backbone links such as OC-192.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Absolute units such as *picoseconds* are more common in microprocessor applications.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Units of *degrees* and *radians* are also used.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] If jitter has a Gaussian distribution, it is usually quantified using the standard deviation of this distribution.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] This translates to an RMS measurement for a zero-mean distribution.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Often, jitter distribution is significantly non-Gaussian.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] This can occur if the jitter is caused by external sources such as power supply noise.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In these cases, *peak-to-peak* measurements may be more useful.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Many efforts have been made to meaningfully quantify distributions that are neither Gaussian nor have a meaningful peak level.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] All have shortcomings but most tend to be good enough for the purposes of engineering work.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In computer networking, *jitter* can refer to packet delay variation, the variation (statistical dispersion) in the delay of the packets.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] One of the main differences between random and deterministic jitter is that deterministic jitter is bounded and random jitter is unbounded.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Random jitter, also called Gaussian jitter, is unpredictable electronic timing noise.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Random jitter typically follows a normal distribution due to being caused by thermal noise in an electrical circuit.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] in which the value of *n* is based on the BER required of the link.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A common BER used in communication standards such as Ethernet is 10−12.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog conversion of signals, the sampling is normally assumed to be periodic with a fixed period—the time between every two samples is the same.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] If there is jitter present on the clock signal to the analog-to-digital converter or a digital-to-analog converter, the time between samples varies and instantaneous signal error arises.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The error is proportional to the slew rate of the desired signal and the absolute value of the clock error.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The effect of jitter on the signal depends on the nature of the jitter.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Random jitter tends to add broadband noise while deterministic jitter tends to add errant spectral components, *birdys*.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In some conditions, less than a nanosecond of jitter can reduce the effective bit resolution of a converter with a Nyquist frequency of 22 kHz to 14 bits.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Sampling jitter is an important consideration in high-frequency signal conversion, or where the clock signal is especially prone to interference.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In digital antenna arrays ADC and DAC jitters are the important factors determining the direction of arrival estimation accuracy and the depth of jammers suppression.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In the context of computer networks, packet jitter or packet delay variation (PDV) is the variation in latency as measured in the variability over time of the end-to-end delay across a network.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A network with constant delay has no packet jitter.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Packet jitter is expressed as an average of the deviation from the network mean delay.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] PDV is an important quality of service factor in assessment of network performance.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Transmitting a burst of traffic at a high rate followed by an interval or period of lower or zero rate transmission may also be seen as a form of jitter, as it represents a deviation from the average transmission rate.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] However, unlike the jitter caused by variation in latency, transmitting in bursts may be seen as a desirable feature, e.g. in variable bitrate transmissions.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Video or image jitter occurs when the horizontal lines of video image frames are randomly displaced due to the corruption of synchronization signals or electromagnetic interference during video transmission.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A model-based dejittering study has been carried out under the framework of digital image and video restoration.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter in serial bus architectures is measured by means of eye patterns.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] There are standards for jitter measurement in serial bus architectures.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The standards cover jitter tolerance, jitter transfer function and jitter generation, with the required values for these attributes varying among different applications.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Where applicable, compliant systems are required to conform to these standards.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Testing for jitter and its measurement is of growing importance to electronics engineers because of increased clock frequencies in digital electronic circuitry to achieve higher device performance.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Higher clock frequencies have commensurately smaller eye openings and thus impose tighter tolerances on jitter.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] For example, modern computer motherboards have serial bus architectures with eye openings of 160 picoseconds or less.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] This is extremely small compared to parallel bus architectures with equivalent performance, which may have eye openings on the order of 1000 picoseconds.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter is measured and evaluated in various ways depending on the type of circuit under test.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In all cases, the goal of jitter measurement is to verify that the jitter will not disrupt normal operation of the circuit.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Testing of device performance for jitter tolerance may involve injection of jitter into electronic components with specialized test equipment.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A less direct approach—in which analog waveforms are digitized and the resulting data stream analyzed—is employed when measuring pixel jitter in frame grabbers.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Anti-jitter circuits (AJCs) are a class of electronic circuits designed to reduce the level of jitter in a clock signal.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] AJCs operate by re-timing the output pulses so they align more closely to an idealized clock.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] They are widely used in clock and data recovery circuits in digital communications, as well as for data sampling systems such as the analog-to-digital converter and digital-to-analog converter.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Examples of anti-jitter circuits include phase-locked loop and delay-locked loop.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Jitter buffers or de-jitter buffers are buffers used to counter jitter introduced by queuing in packet-switched networks to ensure continuous playout of an audio or video media stream transmitted over the network.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The maximum jitter that can be countered by a de-jitter buffer is equal to the buffering delay introduced before starting the play-out of the media stream.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] In the context of packet-switched networks, the term *packet delay variation* is often preferred over *jitter*.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Some systems use sophisticated delay-optimal de-jitter buffers that are capable of adapting the buffering delay to changing network characteristics.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] The adaptation logic is based on the jitter estimates computed from the arrival characteristics of the media packets.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Adjustments associated with adaptive de-jittering involve introducing discontinuities in the media play-out, which may be noticeable to the listener or viewer.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] Adaptive de-jittering is usually carried out for audio play-outs that include voice activity detection, which allows the lengths of the silence periods to be adjusted, thus minimizing the perceptual impact of the adaptation.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A dejitterizer is a device that reduces jitter in a digital signal.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A dejitterizer usually consists of an elastic buffer in which the signal is temporarily stored and then retransmitted at a rate based on the average rate of the incoming signal.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A dejitterizer may not be effective in removing low-frequency jitter (wander).
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A filter can be designed to minimize the effect of sampling jitter.
[src:deterministic-networking/jitter] A jitter signal can be decomposed into intrinsic mode functions (IMFs), which can be further applied for filtering or dejittering.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:deterministic-networking/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:deterministic-networking/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:deterministic-networking/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The majority of projects define extensions to the IEEE 802.1Q – Bridges and Bridged Networks, which describes virtual LANs and network switches.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These extensions in particular address transmission with very low latency and high availability.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Applications include converged networks with real-time audio/video streaming and real-time control streams which are used in automotive applications and industrial control facilities.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Standard information technology network equipment has no concept of "time" and cannot provide synchronization and precision timing.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Delivering data reliably is more important than delivering within a specific time, so there are no constraints on delay or synchronization precision.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Even if the average hop delay is very low, individual delays can be unacceptably high.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Network congestion is handled by throttling and retransmitting dropped packets at the transport layer, but there are no means to prevent congestion at the link layer.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Data can be lost when the buffers are too small or the bandwidth is insufficient, but excessive buffering adds to the delay, which is unacceptable when low deterministic delays are required.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The different AVB/TSN standards documents specified by IEEE 802.1 can be grouped into three basic key component categories that are required for a complete real-time communication solution based on switched Ethernet networks with deterministic quality of service (QoS) for point-to-point connections.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Each and every standard specification can be used on its own and is mostly self-sufficient.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] However, only when used together in a concerted way, can TSN achieve its full potential as a communication system.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE AVB/TSN suite serves as the foundation for deterministic networking to satisfy the common requirements of these applications.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN can handle rate-constrained traffic, where each stream has a bandwidth limit defined by minimum inter-frame intervals and maximal frame size, and time-trigger traffic with an exact accurate time to be sent.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Low-priority traffic is passed on a best-effort basis, with no timing and delivery guarantees.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to standard Ethernet according to IEEE 802.3 and Ethernet bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q, time is very important in TSN networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] For real-time communication with hard, non-negotiable time boundaries for end-to-end transmission latencies, all devices in this network need to have a common time reference and therefore, need to synchronize their clocks among each other.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This is not only true for the end devices of a communication stream, such as an industrial controller and a manufacturing robot, but also true for network components, such as Ethernet switches.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Only through synchronized clocks is it possible for all network devices to operate in unison and execute the required operation at exactly the required point in time.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Although time synchronization in TSN networks can be achieved with GPS clock, this is costly and there is no guarantee that the endpoint device has access to the radio or satellite signal at all times.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Due to these constraints, time in TSN networks is usually distributed from one central time source directly through the network itself using the IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol, which utilizes Ethernet frames to distribute time synchronization information.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS is a tightly constrained subset of IEEE 1588 with sub-microsecond precision and extensions to support synchronisation over WiFi radio (IEEE 802.11).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The idea behind this profile is to narrow the huge list of different IEEE 1588 options down to a manageable few critical options that are applicable to home networks or networks in automotive or industrial automation environments.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS-2011 defines the Generalized Precision Time Protocol (gPTP) profile which, like all profiles of IEEE 1588, selects among the options of 1588, but also generalizes the architecture to allow PTP to apply beyond wired Ethernet networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These calculated delays are then referenced to the GrandMaster (GM) clock in a bridge elected by the Best Master Clock Algorithm, a clock Spanning Tree Protocol to which all Clock Master (CM) and endpoint devices attempt to synchronize.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that does not synchronize to timing messages is outside of the timing domain boundaries (Figure 2).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Synchronization accuracy depends on precise measurements of link delay and frame residence time.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1AS uses *logical syntonization*, where a ratio between local clock and GM clock frequencies is used to calculate synchronized time, and a ratio between local and GM clock frequencies to calculate propagation delay.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE802.1AS-2020 introduces improved time measurement accuracy and support for multiple time domains for redundancy.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Scheduling and traffic shaping allow for the coexistence of different traffic classes with different priorities on the same network – each with different requirements for available bandwidth and end-to-end latency.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic shaping refers to the process of distributing frames/packets evenly in time to smooth out the traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Without traffic shaping at sources and bridges, the packets will *bunch*, i.e., agglomerate into bursts of traffic, overwhelming the buffers in subsequent bridges/switches along the path.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Standard bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q uses a strict priority scheme with eight distinct priorities.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] On the protocol level, these priorities are visible in the Priority Code Point (PCP) field in the 802.1Q VLAN tag of a standard Ethernet frame.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These priorities already distinguish between more important and less important network traffic, but even with the highest of the eight priorities, no absolute guarantee for an end-to-end delivery time can be given.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The reason for this is buffering effects inside the Ethernet switches.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If a switch has started the transmission of an Ethernet frame on one of its ports, even the highest-priority frame has to wait inside the switch buffer for this transmission to finish.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] With standard Ethernet switching, this nondeterminism cannot be avoided.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This is not an issue in environments where applications do not depend on the timely delivery of single Ethernet frames - such as office IT infrastructures.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In these environments, file transfers, emails or other business applications have limited time sensitivity themselves and are usually protected by other mechanisms further up the protocol stack, such as the Transmission Control Protocol.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In industrial automation (Programmable Logic Controller (PLC) with an industrial robot) and automotive car environments, where closed loop control or safety applications are using the Ethernet network, reliable and timely delivery is of utmost importance.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN enhances standard Ethernet communication by adding mechanisms to provide different time slices for different traffic classes and ensure timely delivery with soft and hard real-time requirements of control system applications.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The mechanism of utilizing the eight distinct VLAN priorities is retained, to ensure complete backward compatibility to non-TSN Ethernet.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time-sensitive traffic has several priority classes.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] For credit-based shaper 802.1Qav, Stream Reservation Class A is the highest priority with a transmission period of 125 μs; Class B has the second-highest priority with a maximum transmission period of 250 μs.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic classes shall not exceed their preconfigured maximum bandwidth (75% for audio and video applications).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The worst-case latency requirement is defined as 2 ms for Class A and 50 ms for Class B, but has been shown to be unreliable.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The per-port peer delay provided by gPTP and the network bridge residence delay are added to calculate the accumulated delays and ensure the latency requirement is met.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Control traffic has the third-highest priority and includes gPTP and SRP traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler 802.1Qbv introduces Class CDT for real-time control data from sensors and command streams to actuators, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and a maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Class CDT takes the highest priority over classes A, B, and control traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qav Forwarding and Queuing Enhancements for Time-Sensitive Streams defines traffic shaping using priority classes, which is based on a simple form of leaky bucket credit-based fair queuing.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qav is designed to reduce buffering in receiving bridges and endpoints.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The credit-based shaper defines credits in bits for two separate queues, dedicated to Class A and Class B traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Thus the idleSlope is the bandwidth reserved for the queue by the bridge, and the sendSlope is the transmission rate of the port MAC service.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If the credit is negative and no frames are transmitted, credit increases at *idleSlope* rate until zero is reached.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If an AVB frame cannot be transmitted because a non-AVB frame is in transmission, credit accumulates at *idleSlope* rate, but positive credit is allowed.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Additional limits hiCredit and loCredit are derived from the maximum frame size and maximum interference size, the idleSlope/sendSlope, and the maximum port transmission rate.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Reserved AV stream traffic frames are forwarded with high priority over non-reserved best-effort traffic, subject to credit-based traffic shaping rules which may require them to wait for a certain amount of credits.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This protects best-effort traffic by limiting the maximum AV stream burst.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The frames are scheduled very evenly, though only on an aggregate basis, to smooth out the delivery times and reduce bursting and bunching, which can lead to buffer overflows and packet drops that trigger retransmissions.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The increased buffering delay makes re-transmitted packets obsolete by the time they arrive, resulting in frame drops, which reduces the quality of AV applications.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Deriving guaranteed upper bounds on delays in TSN is non-trivial and is currently being researched, e.g., by using the mathematical framework Network Calculus.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qat Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) is a distributed peer-to-peer protocol that specifies admission controls based on resource requirements of the flow and available network resources.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] SRP reserves resources and advertises streams from the sender/source (talker) to the receivers/destinations (listeners); it works to satisfy QoS requirements for each stream and guarantee the availability of sufficient network resources along the entire flow transmission path.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The traffic streams are identified and registered with a 64-bit *StreamID*, made up of the 48-bit MAC address (EUI) and 16-bit *UniqueID* to identify different streams from the same source.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] SRP employs variants of Multiple Registration Protocol (MRP) to register and de-register attribute values on switches/bridges/devices - the Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP), the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), and the Multiple Stream Registration Protocol (MSRP).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Resources are allocated and configured in both the end nodes of the data stream and the transit nodes along the data flow path, with an end-to-end signaling mechanism to detect the success/failure.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case latency is calculated by querying every bridge.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Reservation requests use the general MRP application with the MRP attribute propagation mechanism.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] All nodes along the flow path pass the MRP Attribute Declaration (MAD) specification, which describes the stream characteristics so that bridges could allocate the necessary resources.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If a bridge is able to reserve the required resources, it propagates the advertisement to the next bridge; otherwise, a *talker failed* message is raised.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When the advertisement message reaches the listener, it replies with *listener ready* message that propagates back to the talker.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Successful reservation is only guaranteed when all intermediate nodes support SRP and respond to advertise and ready messages; in Figure 2 above, AVB domain 1 is unable to connect with AVB domain 2.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] SRP uses a decentralized registration and reservation procedure; multiple requests can introduce delays for critical traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qcc-2018 "Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) Enhancements and Performance Improvements" amendment reduces the size of reservation messages and redefines timers so they trigger updates only when link state or reservation is changed.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] CNC implements a per-stream request-response model, where SR class is not explicitly used: end-stations send requests for a specific stream (via edge port) without knowledge of the network configuration, and CNC performs stream reservation centrally.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] MSRP only runs on the link to end-stations as an information carrier between CNC and end-stations, not for stream reservation.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Centralized User Configuration (CUC) is an optional node that discovers end stations, their capabilities and user requirements, and configures delay-optimized TSN features (for closed-loop IACS applications).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Seamless interop with Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) transport is provided.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc allows centralized configuration management to coexist with decentralized, fully distributed configuration of the SRP protocol, and also supports hybrid configurations for legacy AVB devices.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc can be combined with IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) and TSN traffic shapers.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] While the 802.1Qav FQTSS/CBS works very well with soft real-time traffic, worst-case delays are both hop count and network topology dependent.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Pathological topologies introduce delays, so buffer size requirements have to consider network topology.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] CQF can be used with the IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler, IEEE 802.1Qbu frame preemption, and IEEE 802.1Qci ingress traffic policing.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qci Per-Stream Filtering and Policing (PSFP) improves network robustness by filtering individual traffic streams.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] It prevents traffic overload conditions that may affect bridges and the receiving endpoints due to malfunction or Denial of Service (DoS) attacks.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The stream filter uses rule matching to allow frames with specified stream IDs and priority levels and apply policy actions otherwise.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] All streams are coordinated at their gates, similarly to the 802.1Qch signaling.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The flow metering applies predefined bandwidth profiles for each stream.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler is designed to separate the communication on the Ethernet network into fixed length, repeating time cycles.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Within these cycles, different time slices can be configured that can be assigned to one or several of the eight Ethernet priorities.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By doing this, it is possible to grant exclusive use - for a limited time - to the Ethernet transmission medium for those traffic classes that need transmission guarantees and can't be interrupted.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The basic concept is a time-division multiple access (TDMA) scheme.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By establishing virtual communication channels for specific time periods, time-critical communication can be separated from non-critical background traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler introduces Stream Reservation Class CDT for time-critical control data, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms, in addition to classes A and B defined for IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By granting exclusive access to the transmission medium and devices to time-critical traffic classes, the buffering effects in the Ethernet switch transmission buffers can be avoided and time-critical traffic can be transmitted without non-deterministic interruptions.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, each cycle consists of two time slices.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Time slice 1 only allows the transmission of traffic tagged with VLAN priority 3, and time slice 2 in each cycle allows for the rest of the priorities to be sent.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler requires all clocks on all network devices (Ethernet switches and end devices) to be synchronized and the identical schedule to be configured, all devices understand which priority can be sent to the network at any given point in time.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since time slice 2 has more than one priority assigned to it, within this time slice, the priorities are handled according to standard IEEE 802.1Q strict priority scheduling.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of Ethernet transmissions into cycles and time slices can be enhanced further by the inclusion of other scheduling or traffic shaping algorithms, such as the IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this particular example, IEEE 802.1Qav could be assigned to one or two of the priorities that are used in time slice two to distinguish further between audio/video traffic and background file transfers.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The Time-Sensitive Networking Task Group specifies a number of different schedulers and traffic shapers that can be combined to achieve the nonreactive coexistence of hard real-time, soft real-time and background traffic on the same Ethernet infrastructure.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When an Ethernet interface has started the transmission of a frame to the transmission medium, this transmission has to be completely finished before another transmission can take place.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This includes the transmission of the CRC-32 checksum at the end of the frame to ensure a reliable, fault-free transmission.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This inherent property of Ethernet networks - again- poses a challenge to the TDMA approach of the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Just before the end of time slice 2 in cycle n, a new frame transmission is started.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Unfortunately, this frame is too large to fit into its time slice.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since the transmission of this frame cannot be interrupted, the frame infringes the following time slice 1 of the next cycle n+1.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] By partially or completely blocking a time-critical time slice, real-time frames can be delayed up to the point where they cannot meet the application requirements any longer.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This is very similar to the actual buffering effects that happen in non-TSN Ethernet switches, so TSN has to specify a mechanism to prevent this from happening.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler has to ensure that the Ethernet interface is not busy with the transmission of a frame when the scheduler changes from one time slice to the next.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler achieves this by putting a guard band in front of every time slice that carries time-critical traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] During this guard band time, no new Ethernet frame transmission may be started; only already ongoing transmissions may be finished.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The duration of this guard band has to be as long as it takes the maximum frame size to be safely transmitted.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The total time needed for sending this frame is dependent on the link speed of the Ethernet network.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band has to be at least 123.36 μs long.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] With the guard band, the total bandwidth or time that is usable within a time slice is reduced by the length of the guard band.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Note: to facilitate the presentation of the topic, the actual size of the guard band in figure 3 is not to scale, but is significantly smaller than indicated by the frame in figure 2.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, the time slice 1 always contains high-priority data (e.g. for motion control), while time slice 2 always contains best-effort data.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, a guard band needs to be placed at every transition point into time slice 1 to protect the time slice of the critical data stream(s).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To partially mitigate the loss of bandwidth through the guard band, the standard IEEE 802.1Qbv includes a length-aware scheduling mechanism.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism is used when store-and-forward switching is utilized: after the full reception of an Ethernet frame that needs to be transmitted on a port where the guard band is in effect, the scheduler checks the overall length of the frame.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] If the frame can fit completely inside the guard band, without any infringement of the following high-priority slice, the scheduler can send this frame, despite an active guard band, and reduce the waste of bandwidth.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism, however, cannot be used when cut-through switching is enabled, since the total length of the Ethernet frame needs to be known a priori.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, when cut-through switching is used to minimize end-to-end latency, the waste of bandwidth will still occur.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Also, this does not help with the minimum achievable cycle time.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, length-aware scheduling is an improvement, but cannot mitigate all drawbacks that are introduced by the guard band.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To further mitigate the negative effects of the guard bands, the IEEE working groups 802.1 and 802.3 have specified the frame pre-emption technology.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The two working groups collaborated in this endeavour since the technology required both changes in the Ethernet Media Access Control (MAC) scheme that is under the control of IEEE 802.3, as well as changes in the management mechanisms that are under the control of IEEE 802.1.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Due to this fact, frame pre-emption is described in two different standards documents: IEEE 802.1Qbu for the bridge management component and IEEE 802.3br for the Ethernet MAC component.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption defines two MAC services for an egress port: preemptable MAC (pMAC) and express MAC (eMAC).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Express frames can interrupt the transmission of preemptable frames.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] On resume, MAC merge sublayer reassembles frame fragments in the next bridge.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Preemption causes computational overhead in the link interface, as the operational context shall be transitioned to the express frame.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Figure 4 gives a basic example how frame pre-emption works.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] During the process of sending a best effort Ethernet frame, the MAC interrupts the frame transmission just before the start of the guard band.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The partial frame is completed with a CRC and will be stored in the next switch to wait for the second part of the frame to arrive.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] After the high-priority traffic in time slice 1 has passed and the cycle switches back to time slice 2, the interrupted frame transmission is resumed.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption always operates on a pure link-by-link basis and only fragments from one Ethernet switch to the next Ethernet switch, where the frame is reassembled.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to fragmentation with the Internet Protocol (IP), no end-to-end fragmentation is supported.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Each partial frame is completed by a CRC-32 for error detection.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to the regular Ethernet CRC-32, the last 16 bits are inverted to make a partial frame distinguishable from a regular Ethernet frame.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In addition, the start of frame delimiter (SFD) is changed.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The support for frame pre-emption has to be activated on each link between devices individually.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To signal the capability for frame pre-emption on a link, an Ethernet switch announces this capability through the LLDP (Link Layer Discovery Protocol).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When a device receives such an LLDP announcement on a network port and supports frame pre-emption itself, it may activate the capability.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] There is no direct negotiation and activation of the capability on adjacent devices.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that receives the LLDP pre-emption announcement assumes that on the other end of the link, a device is present that can understand the changes in the frame format (changed CRC-32 and SFD).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption allows for a significant reduction of the guard band.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The length of the guard band is now dependent on the precision of the frame pre-emption mechanism: how small is the minimum size of the frame that the mechanism can still preempt.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.3br specifies the best accuracy for this mechanism at 64 bytes – due to the fact that this is the minimum size of a still valid Ethernet frame.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band can be reduced to a total of 127 bytes: 64 bytes (minimum frame) + 63 bytes (remaining length that cannot be pre-empted).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] All larger frames can be pre-empted again and therefore, there is no need to protect against this size with a guard band.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This minimizes the best effort bandwidth that is lost and also allows for much shorter cycle times at slower Ethernet speeds, such as 100 Mbit/s and below.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Since the pre-emption takes place in hardware in the MAC, as the frame passes through, cut-through switching can be supported as well, since the overall frame size is not needed a priori.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The MAC interface just checks in regular 64-byte intervals whether the frame needs to be preempted or not.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The combination of time synchronization, the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler and frame pre-emption already constitutes an effective set of standards that can be utilized to guarantee the coexistence of different traffic categories on a network while also providing end-to-end latency guarantees.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This will be enhanced further as new IEEE 802.1 specifications, such as 802.1Qch are finalized.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Overall, the time-aware scheduler has high implementation complexity and its use of bandwidth is not efficient.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Task and event scheduling in endpoints has to be coupled with the gate scheduling of the traffic shaper in order to lower the latencies.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] A critical shortcoming is that some delay is incurred when an endpoint streams unsynchronized data, due to the waiting time for the next time-triggered window.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler requires tight synchronization of its time-triggered windows, so all bridges on the stream path must be synchronized.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] However, synchronizing TSN bridge frame selection and transmission time is nontrivial even in moderately sized networks and requires a fully managed solution.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption is hard to implement and has not seen wide industry support.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Credit-based, time-aware and cyclic (peristaltic) shapers require network-wide coordinated time and utilize network bandwidth inefficiently, as they enforce packet transmission at periodic cycles.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaper (ATS) operates asynchronously based on local clocks in each bridge, improving link utilization for mixed traffic types, such as periodic with arbitrary periods, sporadic (event driven), and rate-constrained.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] ATS employs the urgency-based scheduler (UBS), which prioritizes urgent traffic using per-class queuing and per-stream reshaping.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Asynchronicity is achieved by interleaved shaping with traffic characterization based on Token Bucket Emulation, a token bucket emulation model, to eliminate the burstiness cascade effects of per-class shaping.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The TBE shaper controls the traffic by average transmission rate, but allows a certain level of burst traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] When there is a sufficient number of tokens in the bucket, transmission starts immediately; otherwise, the queue's gate closes for the time needed to accumulate enough tokens.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of queuing has low implementation complexity while ensuring that frames with higher priority will bypass the lower priority frames.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The shared queues are highly isolated, with policies for separate queues for frames from different transmitters, the same transmitter but different priority, and the same transmitter and priority but a different priority at the receiver.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Queue isolation prevents propagation of malicious data, assuring that ordinary streams will get no interference, and enables flexible stream or transmitter blocking by administrative action.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The minimum number of shared queues is the number of ports minus one, and more with additional isolation policies.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Shared queues have scheduler internal fixed priority, and frames are transmitted on the First Come First Serve principle.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case clock sync inaccuracy does not decrease link utilization, contrary to time-triggered approaches such as TAS (Qbv) and CQF (Qch).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) specifies extensions to the Intermediate Station to Intermediate Station (IS-IS) protocol to configure multiple paths in bridged networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qca standard uses Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) with a software-defined networking (SDN) hybrid mode - the IS-IS protocol handles basic functions, while the SDN controller manages explicit paths using Path Computation Elements (PCEs) at dedicated server nodes.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qca integrates control protocols to manage multiple topologies, configure an explicit forwarding path (a predefined path for each stream), reserve bandwidth, provides data protection and redundancy, and distribute flow synchronization and flow control messages.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] These are derived from Equal Cost Tree (ECT), Multiple Spanning Tree Instance (MSTI) and Internal Spanning Tree (IST), and Explicit Tree (ET) protocols.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1CB Frame Replication and Elimination for Reliability (FRER) sends duplicate copies of each frame over multiple disjoint paths to provide proactive seamless redundancy for control applications that cannot tolerate packet losses.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The packet replication can use traffic class and path information to minimize network congestion.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Each replicated frame has a sequence identification number, used to re-order and merge frames and to discard duplicates.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] FRER requires centralized configuration management and needs to be used with 802.1Qcc and 802.1Qca.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Industrial fault-tolerance HSR and PRP specified in IEC 62439-3 are supported.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] MRP state data for a stream takes 1500 bytes.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] With additional traffic streams and larger networks, the size of the database proportionally increases and MRP updates between bridge neighbors significantly slow down.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The Link-Local Registration Protocol (LRP) is optimized for a larger database size of about 1 Mbyte with efficient replication that allows incremental updates.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Unresponsive nodes with stale data are automatically discarded.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] While MRP is application specific, with each registered application defining its own set of operations, LRP is application neutral.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE P802.1Qdd project updates the distributed configuration model by defining new peer-to-peer Resource Allocation Protocol signaling built upon P802.1CS Link-local Registration Protocol.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] RAP will improve scalability and provide dynamic reservation for a larger number of streams with support for redundant transmission over multiple paths in 802.1CB FRER, and autoconfiguration of sequence recovery.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] RAP supports the 'topology-independent per-hop latency calculation' capability of TSN shapers such as 802.1Qch Cyclic Queuing and Forwarding (CQF) and P802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaping (ATS).
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] It will also improve performance under high load and support proxying and enhanced diagnostics, all while maintaining backward compatibility and interoperability with MSRP.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE P802.1ABdh Station and Media Access Control Connectivity Discovery - Support for Multiframe Protocol Data Units (LLDPv2) updates LLDP to support IETF Link State Vector Routing protocol and improve efficiency of protocol messages.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] YANG is a Unified Modeling Language (UML) for configuration and state data, notifications, and remote procedure calls, to set up device configuration with network management protocols such as NETCONF/RESTCONF.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) Working Group is focusing on defining deterministic data paths with high reliability and bounds on latency, loss, and packet delay variation (jitter), such as audio and video streaming, industrial automation, and vehicle control.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The goals of Deterministic Networking are to migrate time-critical, high-reliability industrial and audio-video applications from special-purpose Fieldbus networks to IP packet networks.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] To achieve these goals, DetNet uses resource allocation to manage buffer sizes and transmission rates in order to satisfy end-to-end latency requirements.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Service protection against failures with redundancy over multiple paths and explicit routes to reduce packet loss and reordering.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] The same physical network shall handle both time-critical reserved traffic and regular best-effort traffic, and unused reserved bandwidth shall be released for best-effort traffic.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] DetNet operates at the IP Layer 3 routed segments using a software-defined networking layer to provide IntServ and DiffServ integration, and delivers services over lower Layer 2 bridged segments using technologies such as MPLS and IEEE 802.1 AVB/TSN.
[src:deterministic-networking/time-sensitive-networking] Also, the protocol interworking defined by IEEE 802.1CB is used to advertise TSN sub-network capabilities to DetNet flows via the Active Destination MAC and VLAN Stream identification functions.
